he photographs inside the imagestrip. We could use a layout such as flexbox to do so, but the math in standard CSS is very simple. If we consider the @@figure@@ element to be 100%25 wide, each image needs to take up 1/5 of the horizontal space:%0a%3c %0a%3c      100%25 &divide; 5 = 20%25%0a%3c %0a%3c Which leads to the following CSS declaration:%0a%3c %0a%3c (:source lang=css:)%0a%3c figure#imagestrip img {%0a%3c    float: left;%0a%3c    width: 20%25;%0a%3c }%0a%3c (:sourceend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c !! Animate The Strip%0a%3c %0a%3c Finally, we have to get the imagestrip moving from left to right. If the containing @@div@@ is 100%25 wide, then each movement of the imagestrip to the left will be measured in increments of that distance:%0a%3c %0a%3c (:source lang=css linenum:)%0a%3c @keyframes slidy {%0a%3c    20%25 { left: 0%25; }%0a%3c    25%25 { left: -100%25; }%0a%3c    45%25 { left: -100%25; }%0a%3c    50%25 { left: -200%25; }%0a%3c    70%25 { left: -200%25; }%0a%3c    75%25 { left: -300%25; }%0a%3c    95%25 { left: -300%25; }%0a%3c    100%25 { left: -400%25; }&nbsp;%0a%3c }%0a%3c (:sourceend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c Each image in the slider will stay framed in the @@div@@ for 20%25 of the total length of the animation, and move for 5%25.%0a%3c %0a%3c We have to call on the animation to get things started:%0a%3c %0a%3c (:source lang=css linenum:)%0a%3c figure { %0a%3c    position: absolute;%0a%3c    width: 500%25;%0a%3c    margin: 0;%0a%3c    top: 0;%0a%3c    left: 0;%0a%3c    animation: 30s slidy ease-in-out infinite;%0a%3c }%0a%3c (:sourceend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c As you can see, making a responsive slider is in many ways easier than making a fixed one.%0a%3c %0a%3c '-(Both the keyframes and animation code is shown without [[http://demosthenes.info:80/blog/217/CSS3-Vendor-Prefixes | vendor prefixes]] in order to save on space &ndash; you can resize your browser window to see the effect on the slider. Images by the always-excellent [[http://stuckincustoms.com | Trey Radcliff]], u